<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-298-596  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 298 596.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  March 27 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Freelance writer faces computer crime charges. (Stuart Goldman)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer industryComputer CrimesLos Angeles. Police DepartmentAccess ControlsLegal IssuesA Current Affair (Television program)Theft of InformationCourt Cases.andO;Person:    Goldman, Stuart (cases).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>FREELANCE WRITER FACES COMPUTER CRIME CHARGES LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA,U.S.A., 1990 MAR 24 (NB) -- Stuart Goldman, 45, faces federal and statecomputer crime charges after police say he rifled the editorial computers ofthe tabloid news show &quot;A Current Affair&quot; for ideas he could sell to otherpublishers.andM;The case was broken by Los Angeles Police Department detective DickRichardson, who works in the LAPD mostly on computer crime.andP;  Richardsonbrought in U.S.andP;  Secret Service agents and alerted Fox's New York operationsto Goldman's alleged activities.andP;  He was arrested hours after accessing theNew York editorial computers of the TV show, authorities say.andM;The computers Goldman is accused of breaking into are Digital Equipment VMXmachines loaded with the Ultrix operating system and software from BASYSInc., a Yonkers, New York-based company which specializes in software for thebroadcasting industry.andP;  One year ago, a BASYS machine in Tampa, Florida wasbroken into by a former station employee who'd accepted a job with thecompetition.andM;Goldman, however, was not an authorized user of the systems into which he'saccused of penetrating.andP;  Reportedly, Goldman had done freelance workpreviously for both &quot;A Current Affair&quot; and its main competitor, &quot;InsideEdition.&quot; He may have gotten access codes from a Fox employee, police say.andM;Goldman was arraigned in Los Angeles on federal charges which could bring hima 5-year jail term and $250,000 fine on March 9.andP;  A hearing on state chargesis pending for March 29.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19900323/Press Contact: John Chapman, BASYS, 914-376-4800)</TEXT></DOC>